<Para>The SRT determines how the object classes are laid out in the DIT by
assigning rule numbers to each object class.  An object class'
superior rule number specifies the object class directly above it in
the DIT.
</Para>
<Para>For example, the object class <Literal>Organization</Literal> (abbreviated with the
acronym <Literal>ORG</Literal> in the SRT) has a superior rule number of 2,
indicating that it is located in the DIT beneath the object class
<Literal>Country</Literal> (<Literal>C</Literal>), which has a rule number of 2.
<Literal>Organization Unit</Literal> (<Literal>OU</Literal>) is located beneath
<Literal>Organization</Literal> because it has a superior rule number of 3 and so
forth.
</Para>
<Para><IndexTerm Id="DCEADG.GDSIG.indx.48">
<Primary>structured object classes</Primary>
</IndexTerm>
<IndexTerm Id="DCEADG.GDSIG.indx.49">
<Primary>GDS</Primary>
<Secondary>Standard Schema</Secondary>
<Tertiary>structured object classes</Tertiary>
</IndexTerm>The SRT only contains structured object classes; that is, classes
that form branches in the DIT.  Other object classes, such as abstract
and alias classes, are not included.
</Para>
<Para><IndexTerm Id="DCEADG.GDSIG.indx.50">
<Primary>naming</Primary>
<Secondary>attributes</Secondary>
</IndexTerm>
<IndexTerm Id="DCEADG.GDSIG.indx.51">
